    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-25T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-25T12:00:00-05:00" n="329"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14215a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-25T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 25, 1938—noon.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>360. I should appreciate your estimate and that of Ambassador Johnson as to the
                    question of the bearing of the Munich agreement <pb facs="0340" n="336"
                        xml:id="pg_336"/> and its aftermath upon the Japanese decision to invade
                    south China and upon manifestation by the Japanese of an increasingly truculent
                    attitude. As indicative of such attitude reference is made <hi rend="italic"
                        >inter alia</hi> (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) to recent communications from
                    the Japanese evidencing an intention to close the Yangtze and the Pearl Rivers
                    to all shipping<note n="57" xml:id="d329fn57">See <ref
                            target="frus1938v04#pg_143">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, pp.
                            143</ref> ff.</note> until Japanese interests have been served and (<hi
                        rend="italic">b</hi>) to press reports from Tokyo that the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Yomiuri</hi> carried in its issue of October 23 a 5-column advertisement by
                    the Shiunso, a reactionary organization, appealing to the Japanese people to
                    rise and “be prepared to chastise the British”. Please give outline of the
                    reasoning upon which your estimate is based.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
